WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.320 --> 00:00:01.192
Listen to this!

00:00:06.720 --> 00:00:11.644
On the first day of the US–Israeli attacks on&nbsp;
Iran, something strange appeared on the airwaves.

00:00:12.160 --> 00:00:15.920
A mysterious shortwave radio&nbsp;
broadcast: a man’s voice,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:15.920 --> 00:00:18.625
calmly reading random number sequences in Persian.

00:00:21.120 --> 00:00:25.872
Radio enthusiasts first picked it up on&nbsp;
February 28, the first day of the war.

00:00:26.160 --> 00:00:31.280
The broadcast follows a loose pattern: a&nbsp;
string of numbers read aloud for two rounds,

00:00:31.280 --> 00:00:35.320
then a pause, then the Persian word&nbsp;
for “attention” repeated three times.

00:00:35.320 --> 00:00:39.760
And then the numbers start again. Sometimes&nbsp;
it’s longer. Sometimes it’s shorter.

00:00:39.760 --> 00:00:42.480
No one knows exactly where&nbsp;
the signal is coming from.

00:00:42.480 --> 00:00:46.000
But radio enthusiasts have narrowed it&nbsp;
down to somewhere in Western Europe.

00:00:46.480 --> 00:00:50.973
Five days into the war, things got even&nbsp;
stranger. Someone started jamming the signal.

00:00:51.680 --> 00:00:56.644
Electronic noise suddenly flooded the frequency,&nbsp;
making the numbers nearly impossible to hear.

00:00:57.040 --> 00:01:00.664
But the broadcast didn’t stop, it&nbsp;
just moved to a different frequency.

00:01:01.120 --> 00:01:05.200
RFE/RL independently recorded&nbsp;
the transmission on March 10,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:05.200 --> 00:01:08.680
meaning it has been broadcasting&nbsp;
around two weeks. More or less daily.

00:01:09.280 --> 00:01:10.160
So, what is it?

00:01:10.160 --> 00:01:11.920
The most common explanation is something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:11.920 --> 00:01:16.240
called a “numbers station,” an&nbsp;
old-school Cold War spy tool,

00:01:16.240 --> 00:01:19.280
a shortwave radio broadcast&nbsp;
used to send encrypted messages

00:01:19.280 --> 00:01:21.344
to intelligence agents around the world.

00:01:21.920 --> 00:01:24.880
Anyone can listen to the&nbsp;
numbers. But without the decoder,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:24.880 --> 00:01:27.489
the message is essentially&nbsp;
impossible to understand.

00:01:28.160 --> 00:01:31.520
Akin Fernandez, who’s considered&nbsp;
a guru on the subject of “numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:31.520 --> 00:01:34.336
stations,” says it's “absolutely unbreakable.”

00:01:34.720 --> 00:01:39.880
The number keys are perfectly random and figuring&nbsp;
it out mathematically wouldn’t really work either.

00:01:40.240 --> 00:01:42.560
And even if you translate them into words,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:42.560 --> 00:01:46.888
the message would likely still make no&nbsp;
sense without the right decoder key.

00:01:47.440 --> 00:01:49.028
OK. That’s the first thing.

00:01:49.520 --> 00:01:51.920
What about the jamming? Who’s jamming the signal?

00:01:51.920 --> 00:01:52.800
And why?

00:01:52.800 --> 00:01:56.068
So, the kind of interference being&nbsp;
used here is called a bubble jammer.

00:01:56.320 --> 00:02:00.632
Basically, it drowns out the signal, so the&nbsp;
transmission is impossible to understand.

00:02:01.040 --> 00:02:05.844
Historically, this kind of jamming was used by&nbsp;
governments trying to block foreign broadcasts.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:07.200
During the Cold War,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:07.200 --> 00:02:12.077
Soviet bloc countries regularly jammed&nbsp;
broadcasts from the BBC, Deutsche Welle

00:02:12.077 --> 00:02:14.320
-- or Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty -- which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:14.320 --> 00:02:17.641
were beaming uncensored news and&nbsp;
information into the Eastern bloc.

00:02:18.480 --> 00:02:24.320
These days, the Persian-language broadcasts&nbsp;
of the BBC and Radio Free Europe’s Radio Farda&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:24.320 --> 00:02:28.400
are also being jammed by the Iranian&nbsp;
government on a similar frequency.

00:02:28.400 --> 00:02:32.800
So, if Tehran was responsible for this&nbsp;
mysterious Persian numbers signal,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:32.800 --> 00:02:36.048
it’s pretty unlikely that Tehran&nbsp;
would be jamming its own signal.

00:02:36.480 --> 00:02:41.360
That brings us back to the original question:&nbsp;
Who’s behind the numbers station broadcast?

00:02:41.360 --> 00:02:45.520
Could be the United States sending&nbsp;
coded messages to agents inside Iran.

00:02:45.520 --> 00:02:46.720
Or maybe it’s Israel.

00:02:46.720 --> 00:02:49.520
Or how about Turkey, which is no&nbsp;
fan of the Iranian government?

00:02:49.520 --> 00:02:51.200
Then it gets even muddier.

00:02:51.200 --> 00:02:54.560
ABC News reports that the US&nbsp;
government had sent an alert&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:54.560 --> 00:02:58.620
to law enforcement agencies about an&nbsp;
intercepted, encrypted transmission.

00:02:59.280 --> 00:03:03.920
The transmissions could "be intended&nbsp;
to activate or provide instructions to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:03.920 --> 00:03:08.080
prepositioned sleeper assets operating&nbsp;
outside the originating country,”

00:03:08.080 --> 00:03:09.920
ABC quoted the alert as saying.

00:03:09.920 --> 00:03:12.660
The CIA did not respond to requests for comment.

00:03:12.960 --> 00:03:14.960
So, for now, the signal remains a mystery.

00:03:14.960 --> 00:03:16.993
What do you think? Let us know in the comments.

